In LaTeX, automatic generation of a table of contents (TOC) is achieved using the `\tableofcontents` command and configuring `\documentclass` and `\RunWithPackages` (usually `bookmark` and `tocloft` for advanced customization). Here's a comprehensive example:

**Minimal Template:**
```latex
\documentclass[11pt,openright]{book}
\usepackage{tocloft} % advanced TOC customization
\usepackage{bookmark} % improve bookmarking
\usepackage{kantlipsum} % dummy text filler

\begin{document}

\RunWithPackages % process packages affecting TOC

\tableofcontents % generate table of contents

\part{Introduction}
\kant[1] % dummy content

\section{Background}
\kant[2]
\subsection{Importance}
\kant[3]
\subsubsection{Why}
\kant[4]

\part{Application}
\section{Implementation}
\kant[5]
\subsection{Details}
\kant[6]

